 critical race and feminist theories to explore the impact of differences based on gender, race, immigration status, and country of origin. The book begins by contextualizing child maltreatment in Latinx families within the pervasive structural racism and inequality in the United States and addressing unique traumas experienced by Latinx families resulting from that inequity. Subsequent chapters address prevention of child maltreatment, responses to maltreatment and healing from trauma with an emphasis on resilience within the Latinx community. Three case studies are used to illustrate and apply concepts from each chapter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aChild abusezUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aChild abusezUnited States. 0aChild welfarezUnited States. 0aHispanic American childrenxSocial conditions. 0aHispanic American familiesxSocial conditions. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh  achild abuse, child neglect, child abuse cases, latinx family dynamics, hispanic family values, hispanic families, child maltreatment, ethnodiversity, latinx cultural values, hispanic cultural values, machismo mindset, machista mindset, resources for health providers, resources for educators, spanish dictionary, english to spanish dictionary, hispanic parenting, latino parenting, latinx parenting, social work for hispanics, social work in marginalized communities, marginalization, marginalized communities, spanish for dummies, learning spanish, familismo, structural racism, structural bias.1 aFaulkner, Monica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLaBrenz, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978822924?locatt=mod